               <head>Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī by Kamāl al-Dīn Ḥusayn Vāʿiẓ Kāshifī</head>
               <msContents
                  class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh94005331 https://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh91005357 https://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008104964">
                  <summary>A Persian didactic treatise on morality for princes called
                        <title>Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī</title> written by Kamāl al-Dīn Ḥusayn Vāʻiẓ Kāshifī
                     and dedicated to the last Timurid ruler, <persName>Sultān Ḥusayn
                        Bāyqarā</persName> (1438-1506; r. 1469-1506), and his son, <persName>Muḥsin
                        Mīrzā</persName>. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903B-item1">
                     <author key="person_167206013">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Kamāl al-Dīn Ḥusayn ibn ʿAlī Vāʿiẓ
                           Kāshifī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">کمال الدّین حسین بن علی واعظ کاشفی </persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_219">Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">اخلاق محسنی</title>
                     <colophon>(f. 122r) Completed by <persName role="scr" key="">Aḥmad Multānī.
                        </persName>
                     </colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. ii+122+iii. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>237</height>
                              <width>134</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>152</height>
                              <width>86</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>India Office stamped foliation. Foliated on every fifth leaf in pencil
                              though the numbers do not correspond. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords on the bottom-left corners of the verso.
                              </catchwords>
                           </p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Partially damaged. Some folios are stuck together. </p>
                           <p>The manuscript was repaired at least once, after which the inner lines
                              of the text box were ruled again. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="17">
                           <p>17 lines per page. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʻlīq; copied in black ink, with headings and overlinings in red.
                           Copyist is <persName role="scr">Aḥmad Multānī</persName>. </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="headpiece">Illuminated polychrome headpiece, mostly in gold
                           (<locus>f. 1v</locus>). </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>F. 1r has a note which reads: اخلاق محسنی Ethé No 2188-2250. </p>
                     <p>F. 122v has a note written by one <persName role="ann">Muḥammad
                           ʿAlī</persName> who introduces himself as a diciple of Yāqūt and another
                        name which reads Najaf ʿAlī Shīrāzī. </p>
                     <p>The majority of pages have marginal notes explaining the meanings of words
                        and phrases in addition to some anecdotes and hadith. </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1857">
                        <decoNote>Brown leather Indian binding, probably dating from the 19th
                           century. </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval seal of former owner <persName role="asn" key="">Khayr
                              al-Dīn</persName> reading <hi rend="italic">Khāksār Khayr al-Dīn
                              ʿAbduh, 1225</hi> (1809/10) (f. 1r). </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Black Government of India Delhi MSS oval stamp (ff. 1r, 2v, 122v). </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1730">Probably early
                        18th century; </origDate>
                     <origPlace>probably Multan, India. </origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Belonged to <persName role="fmo">Khayr al-Dīn</persName> (his seal on f. 1r). </p>
                     <p>Purchased by the Government of India at sale organised by Delhi Prize
                        Agents, 1859. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Acquired by the India Office Library as an administrative deposit in
                           <date>1876</date>. </p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
